ouchers (in East Hornden) and Buttsbury. The placename means ‘people of the district’, from Old English <i>gē</i> ‘district, region’ + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i>.","English: from Middle English <i>Inge</i>, itself either from the Old Norse female personal name <i>Inga</i> (a pet form of such names as <i>Ingi(v)aldr</i>), or from the Scandinavian male personal name <i>Inge</i> (a pet form of such names as <i>Ingiríthr</i>), or the Anglo-Saxon form of such a name, <i>Inga</i>. Unless there are other indications of gender, the two sources cannot be distinguished.","German: probably from the ancient Germanic female personal name <i>Inga</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Ing","meanings":["English (Buckinghamshire and Middlesex): variant of   Inge  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): nickname from Yiddish <i>ing</i> ‘young’.","Chinese: alternative Cantonese form of the surnames 應, 嬴, and 英, see   Ying   1-3."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Inge I was born in 1148, in Truro, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom as the son of Inge. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1189, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1148–1189":"1148–1189","1189–Male":"1189–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1148":"1148","1189":"1